1950s were time of great prosperity

 GI Bill, which gave military veterans affordable access to a college education added to educated workforce
Jobs readily available

Competitors in europe and asia were still recovering from being bombed
Eisenhower took a middle route, not completely rolling back the New Deal, even expanding some parts

Large focus on balancing national budget- favored low taxes but not if they were gonna send country into debt
	
Huge rise in consumer spending. People had been living meagerly for years and finally had the opportunity to spend. Became much more likely to buy things that weren’t actually required, along with throw away things rather than reuse
“Buy now, pay later” became popular, sending many into debt while they lived lavish lives.
About 25% of americans still lived in poverty, but they were largely ignored
https://www.shmoop.com/1950s/economy.html

The US economically supported the redevelopment strategies of its cold war allies
Military industries often stayed prominent ex: aircraft
Houses became much more affordable

The United States Objectives and Programs for National Security, better known as NSC 68,
Promoted a large increase in military spending
	Probably made it easier to pay for computer research
Eisenhower made space exploration a priority
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economic_history_of_the_United_States#Computer_Technology
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSC_68

Economic aid flowed to war-ravaged European countries under the Marshall Plan, which also helped 
maintain markets for numerous U.S. goods
More people began holding white collar jobs rather than blue collar
Farming declined in terms of employment
https://www.thoughtco.com/the-post-war-us-economy-1945-to-1960-1148153

Military industrial complex-- economy boomed in part due to military contracts
http://www.independent.org/publications/article.asp?id=141




Technologies especially aircraft and computers continued to be funded due to the cold war. Without it, after WW2 ended the funding likely would have stopped
https://ethw.org/A_Brief_History_of_the_U.S._Federal_Government_and_Innovation_Part_III_World_War_II_and_Beyond_1945_%E2%80%93_1987
